erived from <i>īd</i> ‘work’. This died out during the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, influenced by its use in  Tennyson's  The Princess (  1847 ) for the central character, who devotes herself to the cause of women's rights and women's education in a thoroughly Victorian way. The name is also associated with Mount Ida in Crete, which was connected in classical times with the worship of Zeus, king of the gods, who was supposed to have been brought up in a cave on the mountainside. In the 1930s it became famous as the name of the film star  Ida Lupino  (  1914–1995 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":16,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":26,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":36,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Iva de Daresbury was born in 1070, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1122, in Frodsham, Cheshire, England, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1070–1122":"1070–1122","1110–Male":"1110–Surnud","1106":"1106","1122":"1122","1110":"1110","10